#3a REAL ESTATE
#Step 3a: Address missing data
print(f"Shape Before NAs: {df.shape}")
df.dropna(axis=0, inplace = True, how='all')
print(f"Shape After NAs: {df.shape}")
# Cleansing the Unkown Value
missing_values = ["***Unknown***"]
df  = pd.read_csv('RealEstate_Sales.csv', na_values = missing_values)
df.dropna(axis = 0, inplace = True, how = 'all')

#change null values in Property Type, Residential Type, Assessor Remarks, Non Use Code, OPM remarks, Update date
df['Property Type'].fillna(df['Property Type'].mode()[0], inplace = True)
df['Residential Type'].fillna(df['Residential Type'].mode()[0], inplace = True)
df['Assessor Remarks'].fillna(df['Assessor Remarks'].mode()[0], inplace = True)
df['Non Use Code'].fillna(df['Non Use Code'].mode()[0], inplace = True)
df['OPM remarks'].fillna(df['OPM remarks'].mode()[0], inplace = True)

#Step 2: Address duplicates
print(f"Shape Before Dups: {df.shape}")
df.drop_duplicates(inplace = True)
print(f"Shape After Dups: {df.shape}")
#Step 3: Convert and Normalize Data Types
df['Date Recorded'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date Recorded'])

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Get the top 5 towns with the most retail sales
top_towns = df['Town'].value_counts(sort=True).head(5)

# Get the bottom 5 towns with the least retail sales
bottom_towns = df['Town'].value_counts(sort=True).tail(5)

# Create the figure and subplots
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 6)) 

# Plot top 5 towns with the most retail sales
ax1.bar(top_towns.index, top_towns.values, color='skyblue')
ax1.set_xlabel('Towns in Connecticut')
ax1.set_ylabel('Number of Sales')
ax1.set_title('Top 5 Towns with the Most Real Estate Sales')

# Plot bottom 5 towns with the least retail sales
ax2.bar(bottom_towns.index, bottom_towns.values, color='salmon')
ax2.set_xlabel('Towns in Connecticut')
ax2.set_ylabel('Number of Sales')
ax2.set_title('Bottom 5 Towns with the Least Retail Sales')

#Save and show :)
plt.savefig('topbot5.png')
plt.show()

# Group by 'List Year' and count the total number of sales for each year
sales_per_year = df.groupby('List Year').size()

# Create a new figure and axis
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 6))

# Plot the unemployment data on the primary y-axis
filtered_df2_sorted = filtered_df2.sort_values('Update date')
ax1.plot(filtered_df2_sorted['Update date'], filtered_df2_sorted['Value'], color='red', label='% Unemployment')
ax1.set_xlabel('Date')
ax1.set_ylabel('% Unemployment', color='red')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='black')
ax1.set_title('% Unemployment Over Time in Connecticut and Total # of Sales per Year')

# Create a second y-axis that shares the same x-axis
ax2 = ax1.twinx()

# Plot the total number of sales per year on the secondary y-axis
sales_per_year.index = pd.to_datetime(sales_per_year.index, format='%Y')
ax2.plot(sales_per_year.index, sales_per_year, color='green', label='Total # of Sales')
ax2.set_ylabel('Total Number of Sales', color='green')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='black')

# Add legends to the plot
ax1.legend(loc='upper left')
ax2.legend(loc='upper right')

# Adjust layout to prevent overlap
fig.tight_layout()

# Show the plot
plt.savefig('unemp_vs_sales.png')
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Select the top 5 towns with the largest total sales
top_5_towns = df['Town'].value_counts(sort=True).head(5)
top5_list = list(top_5_towns.index)

# Get the bottom 5 towns with the lowest mean real estate values
bottom_5_towns = df['Town'].value_counts(sort=True).tail(5)
bottom5_list = list(bottom_5_towns.index)

# Filter the original DataFrame to include only the data for the top 5 and bottom 5 towns
filtered_top_bottom = df[df['Town'].isin(top5_list + bottom5_list)]

# Group the filtered data by 'List Year' and 'Town' and count the number of sales
sales_per_year = filtered_top_bottom.groupby(['List Year', 'Town']).size()

# Iterate over the top 5 towns and plot the total number of sales per year for each town
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 6))
for town in top5_list:
    town_sales = sales_per_year.loc[:, town]
    ax1.plot(town_sales.index, town_sales.values, marker='x', label=town)

# Iterate over the bottom 5 towns and plot the total number of sales per year for each town
for town in bottom5_list:
    town_sales = sales_per_year.loc[:, town]
    ax2.plot(town_sales.index, town_sales.values, marker='o', label=town)

#Set Labels
ax1.set_xlabel('Year')
ax1.set_ylabel('Total Number of Sales')
ax1.set_title('Total Number of Sales per Year for Top 5 Towns')
ax1.legend(loc='upper right', title='Towns', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), ncol=2)
ax1.set_xticks(range(df['List Year'].min(), df['List Year'].max()+1, 2))

ax2.set_xlabel('Year')
ax2.set_ylabel('Total Number of Sales')
ax2.set_title('Total Number of Sales per Year for Bottom 5 Towns')
ax2.legend(loc='upper right', title='Towns', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), ncol=2)
ax2.set_xticks(range(df['List Year'].min(), df['List Year'].max()+1, 2))

# Display the plot
plt.savefig('totalsales_town.png')
plt.show()

In[126]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Get unique residential types
residential_types = filtered_df['Residential Type'].unique()

# Create subplots, adjusting the number of rows based on the number of unique residential types
nrows = len(residential_types)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=1, figsize=(15, 3 * nrows))

# Plot each residential type on a separate subplot
for i in range(len(residential_types)):
    residential_type = residential_types[i]
    ax = axes[i]
    ind_restype = filtered_df[filtered_df['Residential Type'] == residential_type]
    mean_assessed =ind_restype.groupby('List Year')['Assessed Value'].mean()
    mean_sale = ind_restype.groupby('List Year')['Sale Amount'].mean()
    #plot
    mean_assessed.plot(ax=ax, label='Mean Assessed Value', marker='o')
    mean_sale.plot(ax=ax, label='Mean Sale Amount', marker='x')
    #Label 
    ax.set_xlabel('Listing Year')
    ax.set_ylabel('Price')
    ax.set_title(f'{residential_type} Mean Assessed and Sold Prices over the Listing Years')
    ax.legend(loc='upper right', title='Towns', bbox_to_anchor=(1.2, 1), ncol=1)
    ax.set_xticks(range(filtered_df['List Year'].min(), filtered_df['List Year'].max() + 1, 2))

# Adjust layout to prevent overlap
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the subplots
plt.savefig('salevsass.png')
plt.show()

In[128]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10, 10))
 
z_scores = (df[['Assessed Value', 'Sale Amount']] - df[['Assessed Value', 'Sale Amount']].mean()) / df[['Assessed Value', 'Sale Amount']].std()
threshold = 3
filtered_df = df[(z_scores['Assessed Value'].abs() < threshold) & (z_scores['Sale Amount'].abs() < threshold)]
 
# --- Added the code here ---
ax.scatter(x = filtered_df['Assessed Value'], y = filtered_df['Sale Amount'],
          color = 'blue',
          edgecolor = 'white',
          linewidths = .1,
          alpha = .7)
# ---------------------------
plt.title("Scatter Plot of Assessed Value vs Sale Price")
plt.xlabel("Assessed Value")
plt.ylabel("Sale Price")
 
plt.show()
